<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-042-686  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 042 686.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 25 1989 n251 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fed's revolving door spins again. (federal employee turnover)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caldwell, Bruce; Messmer, Ellen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The turnover of federal employees has picked up again since thegovernment suspended its ethics laws during 1990.andP;  The one-yearrelease from anti-bribery and conflict-of-interest laws will allowgovernment employees, especially those working for the Departmentof Defense, to move over into the private sector without abidingby a battery of laws that some find 'excessively restrictive andonerous.' Information resource management (IRM) officials employedwith the government were forced to retain attorneys before takingjobs with private contractors under the stringent ethics laws.andO;The laws were enacted beginning in 1986 following several widelypublicized contract scandals involving government workers andprivate contractors.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationEthicsGovernment OfficialsContractorsLegal Issues.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Pay increase for IRMs and other senior executives. (table)Recent revolving door examples. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>